On the final day of the Constitutional Convention, Benjamin Franklin rose to deliver his closing remarks. He endorsed the Constitution despite its imperfections, but he offered no guarantees. The system, he said, "is likely to be well administred for a Course of Years, and can only end in Despotism as other Forms have done before it, when the People shall become so corrupted as to need Despotic Government, being incapable of any other."

Thomas Jefferson shared the fear but named it differently. He called it "elective despotism," a government chosen by the people that nonetheless rules without constraint. The form of consent, Jefferson understood, does not guarantee the substance of liberty. A republic can vote its way into servitude if citizens stop demanding that power respect its limits.

James Madison, chief architect of the Constitution, explained how it happens. Liberty, he wrote, is endangered not by sudden conquest but by "gradual and silent encroachments," small seizures of power, each too minor to provoke resistance, until the accumulation becomes irreversible.

Franklin warned of the destination. Jefferson named it. Madison described the path.

This year marks the beginning of the United States' 250th anniversary. Anniversaries invite celebration. They should also invite reckoning.

From the vantage point of these founders, what follows should provoke outrage.

Granting immigration enforcement access to Medicaid patient data, turning a health program into a surveillance tool, is not a policy disagreement. It is a violation of privacy and a usurpation of power that strikes at the foundation of the constitutional design.

Madison would recognize it instantly. Power granted for one purpose is quietly repurposed for another, without debate, without law, without consent. A program created to provide medical care is converted, by administrative agreement rather than legislation, into an instrument of enforcement. That is not republican government. It is rule by maneuver.

Jefferson would be harsher. He believed consent must be informed and power exercised openly. A government that invites people to seek care while secretly using that interaction to expose them to enforcement would, in his view, be acting fraudulently. Jefferson despised rule by contrivance. He would call this what it is: deception practiced upon the people, teaching citizens to fear the very institutions meant to serve them.

John Adams would condemn this as rule by artifice rather than law. Adams insisted on "a government of laws, not of men." Law that operates by surprise, through obscure agreements rather than statutes passed in daylight, fails that test. Citizens cannot consent to rules they are never told exist.

George Mason, author of the Virginia Declaration of Rights, would see confirmation of his deepest fear. He refused to sign the Constitution without explicit protections against abuse. Medical privacy, among the most intimate forms of personal security, would, to Mason, be inviolable. Its quiet breach proves what he always warned: power presses hardest on the vulnerable when limits are vague.

Later inheritors of that tradition would be no less severe.

Louis Brandeis warned that government is the most potent teacher. When it becomes lawless, when it repurposes civil programs into surveillance, it teaches contempt for law itself. Even if no one is immediately arrested, the chilling effect is the injury. A people who avoid medical care out of fear are already less free.

William O. Douglas would be unsparing. He believed privacy is not a luxury but a precondition of freedom. Surveillance need not be total to be effective; it need only induce fear. When welfare and policing merge, liberty dissolves quietly, without spectacle.

Hugo Black would reject any attempt to justify this through convenience or balancing tests. Black believed constitutional guarantees mean what they say, or they mean nothing. A policy that bypasses Congress, evades open debate, and erodes privacy through executive maneuver is unconstitutional in spirit, whatever its procedural clothing.

Across centuries, their judgment converges.

This is a violation of privacy because it turns care into liability.

It is a usurpation of power because it redefines authority without law.

It is a betrayal of trust because it relies on secrecy rather than consent.

And it is a dangerous precedent because once civil life becomes a vector for surveillance, there is no principled stopping point.

As we enter our 250th year, the question is not whether our institutions still stand. They do. The question is whether we still demand that they honor their limits, or whether we have become what Franklin feared.

A republic does not lose its liberty when tyranny announces itself.

It loses it when the door is quietly repurposed, when care becomes a trap, when trust becomes exposure, and when power learns it can cross the line without consequence.

Jefferson called it elective despotism: a government chosen by the people, unrestrained by them.

Franklin was blunter. The republic would end in despotism, he said, when the people became "so corrupted as to need Despotic Government, being incapable of any other."

The founders did not warn us about kings.

They warned us about ourselves.

The encroachments are no longer silent. They are visible, documented, and defended. The only question that remains is whether we have become the people Franklin described, so accustomed to the erosion of liberty that we no longer notice it, so corrupted by faction that we no longer resist it, so incapable of self-government that we no longer deserve it.

That is the reckoning this anniversary demands.

Not celebration.

Judgment.

Code Review in the AI Era: Why Writing It Twice Is Actually Faster

If you've been coding for a few years, you've probably lived through this nightmare: you finish the first version, finally get it running, and then realize you misunderstood half the requirements, hit three technical dead ends, and the architecture won't survive the next iteration. Want to rewrite from scratch? The deadline says no. So you keep piling on patches, and three years later, that codebase has become the legacy monster no one dares to touch.

This problem has existed for decades. But AI coding tools have accidentally given us a new solution.

My Approach: Two Versions, Two Standards

This idea isn't new. Software engineering textbooks call it "prototyping", build a rough version to validate your ideas, then do the real development. But nobody actually did this, because it was too expensive. Building a working prototype could take half the time of the real implementation. Who has that kind of runway?

Things have changed. AI writes code at a speed that still catches me off guard. A feature that used to take three days might now have a working version in three hours. This shift in velocity turns prototyping from "theoretically nice" into "practically worth it."

Here's how it works: you build two separate versions.

Version One: The Prototype, Let AI Run Wild

The first version has a clear purpose: it's a prototype, not a product. Two goals only: confirm the requirements and solve the hard technical problems.

The principle here is "no constraints", don't think about architecture, don't worry about code quality, ignore security and performance. Focus on one thing: make it work. Merge AI-generated code without review. Let the AI iterate until your product manager nods and says, "Yes, that's what I wanted."

This code is meant to be thrown away, so put it on a separate branch or even in a standalone repo. Its value isn't in the code itself, it's in two things: figuring out what the requirements actually are, and stepping on all the technical landmines first.

No matter how detailed your requirements doc is, you often can't think clearly until you build something. Technical challenges are the same, theory and reality are different beasts. The first version exists to step on every landmine at the lowest possible cost.

Think of it like an architect's sketch. Sketches don't need precise lines or perfect proportions. They help you externalize your thinking quickly, experiment, adjust, confirm direction. Nobody builds from a sketch.

Version Two: Production, Back to Traditional Engineering

Once the first version has cleared the path, you build the second. This is what actually ships.

Now you return to traditional software engineering: design first, then break it into modules, run CI pipelines, do proper code reviews. Keep commits small so humans can actually review them. Consider design, maintainability, security, all the things that matter.

AI still does the heavy lifting in this phase, but humans lead. Design before implementation. Use plan mode to have AI generate code according to your thinking.

The first version's code isn't completely wasted, some modules can be reused, especially algorithm implementations and core business logic.

It's like extracting the valuable parts from a sketch and putting them into proper construction drawings.

Why This Actually Works

Why go through the trouble of two versions?

The core reason: before the first version is done, your understanding of the requirements is almost certainly incomplete.

The problem with traditional development is that it invests too much effort in the first version. You start architecting before the requirements are fully understood. You consider scalability and maintainability before you've figured out the technical challenges. The result? Massive over-engineering for scenarios that "might happen someday" but never will. Time gets spent on edge cases while the real problems get ignored.

The two-version approach lets you clear the path at minimum cost first. After the first version, requirements are confirmed, technical problems are solved, and then you design‚Äîknowing exactly what to design and what to skip. Far fewer wrong turns.

There's a hidden benefit too. Many senior developers resist AI coding because they can't accept the quality of AI-generated code. But if you tell them this code is meant to be thrown away, it's just for validating ideas, the psychological resistance drops significantly. It's an out: use AI, but don't be responsible for that code.

Ultimately, AI hasn't just changed how fast we write code, it's changed the economics of the entire development process. Two passes used to be too expensive. Now two passes is actually cheaper. Accepting that the first version is disposable lets you build a much better second version.
